Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
createRow(25.10)                                              createRow(25.10)

Name
       createRow - Creates rows for the specified site

Syntax
       createRow

       [-help]

       -site <siteName>

       [-area  {<x1  y1  x2  y2>}  |  -boxList {{<x1 y1>} {<x2 y2>} <...>}< >|
       -polygon {{<x1 y1>} {<x2 y2>}...}]

       [-spacing <distance>]

       [-limitInCore]

       [-noAbut | -noAbut1st]

       [-flip1st]

       [-noCheck]

       [-noFlip]

       Creates rows for the specified site. The row boundary can be defined by
       core area or the area that you specify. This command supports the  cre-
       ation  of  overlapping  rows.  This  command can create only horizontal
       rows. By default, alternate rows are flipped and all rows  are  abutted
       (no spaces between rows).

       The following points apply to the usage of this command:

              * Rows can be created both inside and outside the core area, but
                within the die.

              * All new rows created in an area must be an integer multiple of
                any existing rows in the same area.

              * Non-integer  multiple  height  rows  cannot be created outside
                power domains.

       Use this command after importing a design.

Parameters
       -area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}
              Create rows in the specified rectangle. (Default is  within  the
              core  box.)  The  values are floats, units are microns. Rows are
              truncated at the die box boundary. Either a tcl list or 4  sepa-
              rate parameters works.

              * <x1>: Specifies the lower left x coordinate of the area.

              * y1: Specifies the lower left y coordinate of the area.

              * x2: Specifies the upper right x coordinate of the area.

              * y2: Specifies the upper right y coordinate of the area.

              Data_type: box, optional

       -boxList {{<x1 y1>} {<x2 y2>} ...}
              The  X and Y values are floats, units are microns. There must be
              an even number of points specified. Pairs of points are used  to
              determine a set of rectangles, where the first point of the pair
              is  LLX,  LLY, the second point is URX, URY. Rectangles need not
              be overlapping. Rows are created in the union of the  rectangles
              defined.  Note that for overlapping rectangles, rows are created
              continuously starting at the first (bottom) row (of  the  lowest
              rectangle). For non-overlapping rectangles, rows are created in-
              dependently starting at the bottom of each rectangle.

              Data_type: point_list, optional

       -flip1st
              Controls  the orientation of the first (bottom) row, which is R0
              by default. When -flip1st, the first row's  orientation  is  MX.
              See -noFlip.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each createRow parameter.  For  a  detailed  de-
              scription  of the command and all of its parameters, use the man
              command: man createRow

       -limitInCore
              By default (none of -area, -polygon,  -boxList  specified)  rows
              are  created  in  the  core  box.  When  one of -area, -polygon,
              -boxList is specified, by default rows are  created  within  the
              intersection of the die box and the specified rectilinear shape.
              When one of -area, -polygon, -boxList and -limitInCore is speci-
              fied,  rows  are created within the intersection of the core box
              and the specified rectilinear shape.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -noAbut
              Controls where spaces are inserted  between  rows.  By  default,
              spaces  are  inserted between pairs of rows. When -noAbut is en-
              abled spaces are inserted between every row.  See  -spacing  and
              -noAbut1st.

              Default: The rows are abutted by default.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -noAbut1st
              Controls where the first space between rows is inserted. Default
              is  that  the  first  space is inserted after the first (lowest)
              pair of rows, and subsequently after every pair of  rows  (space
              inserted  between  2nd  and  3rd rows, between 4th and 5th rows,
              etc). When -noAbut1st, the first space  is  inserted  after  the
              first  (lowest)  row,  and subsequently after every pair of rows
              (space inserted between 1st and 2nd rows, then 3rd and 4th rows,
              etc). See -spacing and -noAbut.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -noCheck
              Specifies that  the row should not be aligned  to  the  existing
              row and should support redo undo.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -noFlip
              By  default  rows  have  alternating  orientation  (...MX  R0 MX
              R0...), or when -no_flip_rows is specified rows  have  identical
              orientation  (one  of:  ...R0  R0 R0...; or ...MX MX MX...). See
              -flip1st.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -polygon {{<x1 y1>} {<x2 y2>}...}
              The X and Y values are floats, units are microns. There must  be
              an even number of points specified. The points specify a polygon
              in  which  rows  are  created. Each pair of points specifies one
              edge of the polygon, so { X1 Y1 } and {  X2  Y2  }  specify  one
              edge,  {  X2 Y2 } { X3 Y3 } specify the next edge, etc. The last
              edge is specified by { Xlast Ylast } { X1 Y1 }. In the  degener-
              ate  case  (multiple rectilinear areas touching at corners) rows
              will be created continuously starting at the lowest point.

              Data_type: point_list, optional

       -site <siteName>
              Specifies the name of the site to be used for creating the rows.
              (Objects not allowed.)

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -spacing
              Specifies the width of the space inserted between certain  rows.
              The  first (lowest) row is always inserted along the bottom edge
              of the area having rows added. If  -noAbut  is  specified,  then
              space  is  inserted between every subsequent row. The default is
              space is inserted between every  other  row.  If  -noAbut1st  is
              specified,  then space is inserted after the first row (and then
              the third etc). The default is that space is inserted after  the
              second  row  (and  then  the  4th  etc).  Note  that -noAbut and
              -noAbut1st are mutually exclusive.

              Default: 0.0 um

              Data_type: float, optional

Example
              * The following command creates rows for the site lt3site within
                the area defined by the  coordinates  376.7,  577.57,  688.94,
                725.68,  maintaining  a  spacing of 1 micron between the rows,
                without the first row being abutted:

                createRow -site  lt3site  -area  376.7  577.57  688.94  725.68
                -spacing 1.0 -noAbut1st

              *

                The  following  commands  and images show the functionality of
                the option flip1st

                createRow -area {500 500 550 550} -site tsm3site

                createRow -area {500 500 550 550} -site tsm3site -flip1st

              *

                The following commands and images show  the  functionality  of
                the option limitInCore

                createRow -area {260 260 340 340} -site tsm3site:

                createRow -area {260 260 340 340} -site tsm3site -limitInCore:

              *

                The following commands and images show the capabilities of the
                options spacing,noAbut and noAbut1st:

                createRow -area {620 500 670 550} -site tsm3site -spacing 10:

                createRow  -area  {620 500 670 550} -site tsm3site -spacing 10
                -noAbut:

                createRow -area {620 500 670 550} -site tsm3site  -spacing  10
                -noAbut1st:

              *

                The following commands and images show the capabilities of the
                options noCheck (The placement grid is opened):

                createRow -area {680 500 730 550} -site tsm3site

                createRow -area {680 500 730 550} -site tsm3site -noCheck

              * The following commands and images show the capabilities of the
                option noFlip:

                createRow -area {680 500 730 550} -site tsm3site :

                createRow -area {680 500 730 550} -site tsm3site -noFlip:

